<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.ukri.org/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9"><gtr:id>3EAE04CA-9D62-4483-B9C4-F91AD9F4C5A9</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Oxford</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>University Chest</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Wellington Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Oxford</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>OX1 2JD</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>South East</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/5B22B768-EBA3-479A-AC3B-68470D994933"><gtr:id>5B22B768-EBA3-479A-AC3B-68470D994933</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Thomas</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Klausberger</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=MC_UU_12020%2F6"><gtr:id>1F953499-0B01-45A9-ABC9-14C3A41060AB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Spike timing in identified neuronal circuits of the medial prefrontal cortex</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Intramural</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>MC_UU_12020/6</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This programme aims to identify the activity in defined neuronal circuits of the prefrontal cortex in rats combining a large diversity of anatomical and electrophysiological methods. Human patients with damage to the prefrontal cortex suffer from personality and social impairments. In addition, deficits in the functioning of the prefrontal cortex have been indicated for schizophrenia, attention deficit/hyperactivity disorder, depression and Alzheimer?s disease. By discovering organisational principals in the neuronal circuits of the prefrontal cortex, in this programme we aim to provide the basic biological principles for identifying targets for hypothesis-driven treatment development. For example, a dysfunction of specific subsets of neurons has recently been hypothesized to cause reduced neuronal synchrony in schizophrenia. In the present programme we will record the activity of identified neurons in the prefrontal cortex. This may uncover the consequences of the impairment of defined subsets of neuron and might lead to strategies for treatment of cortical dysfunction.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>This programme will define neuronal operations in prefrontal circuits supporting memory and decision making. The temporal activity in neuronal circuits of the prefrontal cortex reflects emotional information combined with episodic and spatial memory to guide decisions on behavioural action. In this research program three levels of cortical complexity (co-operation between different cortical areas, diversity of neuronal populations, temporal organisation of cortical networks) will be addressed in the medial prefrontal cortex of the rat, which is homologous to the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex of primates. Previously, it has been described in rats that the firing of prefrontal neurons is correlated to the execution of behaviours and/or decision-making. However, the identity of the recorded neurons and their causal contribution to behaviour could not be established in these studies, which is critical for defining the neuronal circuits underlying executive control. In the medial prefrontal cortex of rodents, single neurons with unknown identity exhibit specific firing patterns during spatial decision-making tasks. However, in the cerebral cortex, highly diverse subsets of neurons with distinct synaptic connectivity, molecular expression profile and contribution to network activity exist. In order to discover how neuronal circuits support higher cognitive functions, thus, it is critical to determine the identity and temporal activity of neurons. In the present programme we will record identified neurons in the medial prefrontal cortex of rats during network oscillations and executive control. We will determine the contribution of identified neurons to prefrontal gamma, spindle and 1 Hz oscillations and we will determine ensemble activity of prefrontal neurons during working memory and decision making tasks. In addition, we will develop a novel juxtacellular recording and labelling technique in freely-moving rats. We will use this new technique to discover the synaptic connectivity, molecular machinery, contributions to synchronised network activity and spike timing of identified neurons during decision making. Furthermore, we will use optogenetic techniques, which allow the reversible manipulation of subsets of neurons. The results of these experiments will determine temporal codes of neuronal circuits underlying the selection of behavioural responses and decision-making.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2015-03-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2013-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>EXPENDITURE_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>146000</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>89C16FED-7828-42CE-8166-3525358156BB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Layer-specific GABAergic control of distinct gamma oscillations in the CA1 hippocampus.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Neuron</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/b2baa6427060d8f6666b75dbd6915e1d"><gtr:id>b2baa6427060d8f6666b75dbd6915e1d</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Laszt?czi B</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2014-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0896-6273</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>53b3e44ed6c5e6.53365842</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>2CEF5CBD-C6BD-4309-BE00-8A549BEAEFB2</gtr:id><gtr:title>Temporal organization of GABAergic interneurons in the intermediate CA1 hippocampus during network oscillations.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Cerebral cortex (New York, N.Y. : 1991)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/08f427df616a9b55bb14db745b937991"><gtr:id>08f427df616a9b55bb14db745b937991</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Forro T</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>1047-3211</gtr:issn><gtr:outcomeId>DZNdd1oUHZx</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>84DC8FDF-E3CA-4D8E-BC2B-CD3FD223B3BB</gtr:id><gtr:title>Sleep and movement differentiates actions of two types of somatostatin-expressing GABAergic interneuron in rat hippocampus.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Neuron</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/13f8f5a5808cccb48ef8039a95684b74"><gtr:id>13f8f5a5808cccb48ef8039a95684b74</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Katona L</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:autho